tSocial Licence, Consent, and the Keeyask Project -- tThe Keeyask Model from a Community Economic Development Perspective -- tWhat Is Good Development? Legacy Building in the North -- tHiding from Hydro -- tThe Two-Track Approach: Foundations for Indigenous and Western Frameworks in Environmental Evaluation -- t“The Relation to Our Land” -- tGood Development Should Not End with Environmental Assessment: Adaptive Management in Northern Development -- tWill There Be Lasting Gains? Sustainability Assessment, Keeyask, and the Manitoba Power System Plan -- tPathways to a Better Legacy of Development in Northern Manitoba -- tThe Government of Manitoba’s Apology -- tComments on the Official Apology for Harms Caused by the Hydropower System -- tExcerpts from Economic Review of Bipole III and Keeyask -- tAbbreviations -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBeginning with the Grand Rapids Dam in the 1960s, hydroelectric development has dramatically altered the social, political, and physical landscape of northern Manitoba. The Nelson River has been cut up into segments and fractured by a string of dams, for which the Churchill River had to be diverted and new inflow points from Lake Winnipeg created to manage their capacity. Historic mighty rapids have shrivelled into dry river beds. Manitoba Hydro's Keeyask dam and generating station will expand the existing network of 15 dams and 13,800 km of transmission lines. In Our Backyard tells the story of the Keeyask dam and accompanying development on the Nelson River from the perspective of Indigenous peoples, academics, scientists, and regulators. It builds on the rich environmental and economic evaluations documented in the Clean Environment Commission’s public hearings on Keeyask in 2012. It amplifies Indigenous voices that environmental assessment and regulatory processes have often failed to incorporate and provides a basis for ongoing decision-making and scholarship relating to Keeyask and resource development more generally. It considers cumulative, regional, and strategic impact assessments; Indigenous worldviews and laws within the regulatory and decision-making process; the economics of development; models for monitoring and management; consideration of affected species; and cultural and social impacts. With a provincial and federal regulatory regime that is struggling with important questions around the balance between development and sustainability, and in light of the inherent rights of Indigenous people to land, livelihoods, and self-determination, In Our Backyard offers critical reflections that highlight the need for purposeful dialogue, principled decision making, and a better legacy of northern development in the future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDamsxEnvironmental aspectszManitoba. 0aDamsxSocial aspectszManitoba. 0aDamszManitoba. 0aIndigenous peoplesxCivil rightszManitoba. 0aIndigenous peoplesxLand tenurezManitoba. 0aIndigenous peopleszManitobaxGovernment relations. 0aNatural resourceszManitobaxManagement. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / Native American Studies.2bisacsh1 aBlakley, Jill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlakley, Jill, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBraun, Will, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBuckland, Jerry, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraft, Aimée, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraft, Aimée, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDiduck, Alan P., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDipple, Joseph, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca